.TH "ntfs_write_volume_flags" 9 "ntfs_write_volume_flags" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
ntfs_write_volume_flags \- write new flags to the volume information flags
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" ntfs_write_volume_flags
.BI "(ntfs_volume *vol "  ","
.BI "const VOLUME_FLAGS flags "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "vol" 12
ntfs volume on which to modify the flags
.IP "flags" 12
new flags value for the volume information flags
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
Internal function.  You probably want to use ntfs_{set,clear}\fB_volume_flags\fP
instead (see below).

Replace the volume information flags on the volume \fIvol\fP with the value
supplied in \fIflags\fP.  Note, this overwrites the volume information flags, so
make sure to combine the flags you want to modify with the old flags and use
the result when calling \fBntfs_write_volume_flags\fP.

Return 0 on success and -errno on error.
